Amazon owns a diverse range of businesses across various sectors. Some of the most prominent include Amazon Retail, which is its core e-commerce platform selling a vast array of products from electronics to clothing; Amazon Web Services, a leading cloud computing service providing infrastructure, storage, and computing power to businesses worldwide; Amazon Prime, a subscription service offering free shipping, streaming video and music, and other benefits; Amazon Fresh and Amazon Pantry, which are grocery delivery services; Amazon Devices, including the development and sale of electronic devices such as Kindle e-readers, Fire tablets, Fire TV, and Echo smart speakers; Amazon Studios, which produces original television shows and movies; Amazon Logistics, which manages its delivery and transportation network; and Amazon Advertising, which offers advertising solutions to brands and sellers on its platform. Additionally, Amazon has acquired or invested in other companies such as Whole Foods Market, an organic and natural foods supermarket chain; Audible, an audiobook and spoken-word entertainment service; and Zappos, an online shoe and clothing retailer. The company also owns various subsidiaries and has stakes in different technology and entertainment firms. 

Amazon's business portfolio is extensive and continues to grow as it ventures into new markets and industries.
7: Googles main programming languages include Go, also known as Golang, which was created by Google engineers Robert Griesemer, Rob Pike, and Ken Thompson in 2007 and officially announced in 2009. Another language is Dart, developed by Google and first released in 2011, designed for building web, server, and mobile applications. Additionally, Google has contributed to the development of Python and Java, but these are not created by Google. As of now, the primary programming languages created by Google are Go and Dart.
